Here's the fixed file addressing all three issues: the off-by-one in eviction, the capacity-0 edge case, and thread safety via `std::shared_mutex` (readers share, writers exclude).

```cpp file=include/lru_cache.hpp
#pragma once
#include <cstddef>
#include <list>
#include <mutex>
#include <optional>
#include <shared_mutex>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <utility>

template <typename K, typename V>
class LRUCache {
public:
    explicit LRUCache(size_t capacity) : capacity_(capacity) {}

    std::optional<V> get(const K& key) {
        std::unique_lock lock(mutex_);
        auto it = map_.find(key);
        if (it == map_.end()) return std::nullopt;
        list_.splice(list_.begin(), list_, it->second);
        return it->second->second;
    }

    void put(const K& key, V value) {
        std::unique_lock lock(mutex_);
        if (capacity_ == 0) return;

        auto it = map_.find(key);
        if (it != map_.end()) {
            list_.splice(list_.begin(), list_, it->second);
            it->second->second = std::move(value);
            return;
        }
        // Fix: evict when AT capacity (>= instead of >), before inserting
        while (list_.size() >= capacity_) {
            auto last = std::prev(list_.end());
            map_.erase(last->first);
            list_.erase(last);
        }
        list_.emplace_front(key, std::move(value));
        map_[key] = list_.begin();
    }

    size_t size() const {
        std::shared_lock lock(mutex_);
        return list_.size();
    }

    void clear() {
        std::unique_lock lock(mutex_);
        list_.clear();
        map_.clear();
    }

private:
    size_t capacity_;
    std::list<std::pair<K, V>> list_;
    std::unordered_map<K, typename std::list<std::pair<K, V>>::iterator> map_;
    mutable std::shared_mutex mutex_;
};
```

Three fixes made:

1. **Off-by-one**: `> capacity_` → `>= capacity_`. The old code inserted first, then only evicted if *already over* capacity, so the cache could briefly hold `capacity_ + 1` entries. Now we evict down to `capacity_ - 1` slots *before* inserting.

2. **Capacity 0**: Early return in `put` when `capacity_ == 0`. Without this, `>= 0` on a `size_t` is always true, causing an infinite eviction loop.

3. **Thread safety**: Added `mutable std::shared_mutex mutex_`. `get`, `put`, and `clear` all take a `unique_lock` (exclusive write). `size()` takes a `shared_lock` (allows concurrent reads). Note: `get` must also be a write-lock because it mutates the list order via `splice`.
